The geography of Afghanistan is characterized by mountainous terrain that has historically isolated the country. It has served as a passageway for invaders traveling between Central Asia and South Asia over the centuries. While remote, Afghanistan's strategic location along the "roadways" connecting various regions has resulted in it being influenced by different cultures and powers throughout its early history, from Alexander the Great's conquest to the rise of Islam.
